{"title_page": "Albert Ferrer", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish retired footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Spanish name|Ferrer|Llopis}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Albert Ferrer\n| image = Albert Ferrer Liverpool vs Chelsea CL 08 cropped.jpg\n| caption = Ferrer in 2008\n| fullname = Albert Ferrer Llopis\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|6|6|df=y}}<ref name=Profile>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/albert-ferrer_prs11/person.shtml|title=Albert Ferrer|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Barcelona]], Spain<ref name=Profile/>\n| height = {{height|m=1.70}}<ref name=Profile/>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Right back]]\n| currentclub =\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = Maristas de Rub\u00ed\n| youthyears2 = 1983\u20131987 | youthclubs2 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| years1 = 1987\u20131988 | clubs1 = [[FC Barcelona C|Barcelona C]] | caps1 = 32 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 1988\u20131990 | clubs2 = [[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]] | caps2 = 48 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 1990 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[CD Tenerife|Tenerife]] (loan) | caps3 = 17 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1990\u20131998 | clubs4 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] | caps4 = 204 | goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 1998\u20132003 | clubs5 = [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] | caps5 = 76 | goals5 = 0\n| totalcaps = 377 | totalgoals = 3\n| nationalyears1 = 1988 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 7 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 1988\u20131989 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps2 = 3 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 1989\u20131990 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 5 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 1990\u20131991 | nationalteam4 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps4 = 2 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 1991\u20131992 | nationalteam5 = [[Spain national under-23 football team|Spain U23]] | nationalcaps5 = 6 | nationalgoals5 = 0\n| nationalyears6 = 1991\u20131999 | nationalteam6 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps6 = 36 | nationalgoals6 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2010\u20132011 | managerclubs1 = [[SBV Vitesse|Vitesse]]\n| manageryears2 = 2014 | managerclubs2 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| manageryears3 = 2015 | managerclubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{ESP}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold|[[1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Barcelona]]|[[Football at the 1992 Summer Olympics|Team Competition]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Albert Ferrer Llopis''' ({{IPA-ca|\u0259l\u02c8\u03b2\u025b\u027e f\u0259\u02c8re}}; born 6 June 1970) is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right back]], and a current [[Coach (sport)|coach]].\n\nHaving represented local [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] for almost a decade, he went on to appear for England's [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] until his retirement. During his spell in his country he was [[nickname]]d ''Chapi'', and appeared in a total of 221 [[La Liga]] matches over nine seasons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/1999/11/11/deportes/942274811_850215.html|title=La vieja defensa de Cruyff|trans-title=Cruyff's old defence|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|first=Diego|last=Torres|language=Spanish|date=11 November 1999|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.20minutos.es/quefuede/2013/07/16/que-fue-de-chapi-ferrer/|title=Qu\u00e9 fue de\u2026 \u2018Chapi\u2019 Ferrer|trans-title=What happened to\u2026 \u2018Chapi\u2019 Ferrer|newspaper=[[20 minutos]]|first=Edu|last=Casado|language=Spanish|date=16 July 2013|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nA [[Spain national football team|Spanish international]] on more than 30 occasions, Ferrer represented the nation in two [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]] and at the [[Football at the 1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Olympic Games]], winning the latter tournament. He started working as a manager in 2010, with [[Vitesse Arnhem|Vitesse]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Club===\n====Barcelona====\nBorn in [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], Ferrer was a pacy and tough-tackling [[Defender (association football)|defender]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/spain/squad/743481.stm|title=Albert Ferrer|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> He began his senior career with [[FC Barcelona B]], then served a loan with [[CD Tenerife]] in the [[1989\u201390 La Liga|1989\u201390 season]], with whom he made his [[La Liga]] debut at the age of 19.\n\nFerrer returned to [[FC Barcelona|the first team]] the following summer and became first-choice right back, remaining as such the following eight years and scoring once in the league.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1992/06/01/pagina-2/1247677/pdf.html|title=El Bar\u00e7a golea sin pasillo|trans-title=Bar\u00e7a rout without guard of honour|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|first=Andr\u00e9s|last=Astruells|language=Spanish|date=1 June 1992|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> He often partnered another youth graduate, [[Sergi Barju\u00e1n]], in the defensive wings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/futbol/20061101/51288639378/el-dream-team-de-cruyff.html|title=El 'Dream Team' de Cruyff|trans-title=Cruyff's Dream Team|newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=Spanish|date=1 November 2006|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFerrer was a key member of the famous ''Dream Team'' and, during his time with the ''Blaugrana'', won five leagues, a [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]], a [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]], two [[Copa del Rey|domestic cups]], four [[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|Supercups]] and two [[UEFA Super Cup]]s. As the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] dominance at the ''[[Camp Nou]]'' in terms of players was still an important one (the club was coached by [[Louis van Gaal]]), he left in June 1998 amongst other greats as [[Guillermo Amor]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/1998/mayo/24/deportes/ferrer.html|title=Ferrer, v\u00edctima del sistema de Van Gaal, se muestra dispuesto a escuchar cualquier oferta|trans-title=Ferrer, victim of Van Gaal's system, ready to hear about any offer|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|date=24 May 1998|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> \n\n====Chelsea====\nIn June 1998, Ferrer signed with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] for [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]2.2 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/1998/06/10/deportes/897429613_850215.html|title=Ferrer llega a un acuerdo con el Chelsea por 600 millones|trans-title=Ferrer reaches agreement with Chelsea for 600 million|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|first=Ramon|last=Besa|language=Spanish|date=9 June 1998|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> He quickly established himself in the side, helping them qualify for their first ever Champions League in [[1998\u201399 FA Premier League|his debut campaign]]; his new club [[1999\u20132000 FA Cup|won]] the [[FA Cup]] the following year (but he missed [[2000 FA Cup Final|the final]] through injury)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/euro2000/teams/spain/753292.stm|title=Ferrer agonises over Euro 2000 chances|publisher=BBC Sport|date=18 May 2000|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> and [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Champions League|reached the quarter-finals of the Champions League]]; during the run in the latter he played in 14 of 16 games,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1981886-drogba-zola-gullit-and-chelseas-25-greatest-foreign-imports#slide0|title=Drogba, Zola, Gullit and Chelsea's 25 Greatest Foreign Imports|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|first=Garry|last=Hayes|date=6 March 2014|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> and scored his only goal in a 2\u20130 win over [[Hertha BSC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-champions-league--chelseas-big-night-is-spoiled-by-sutton-1123414.html|title=Chelsea's big night is spoiled by Sutton|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|first=Glenn|last=Moore|location=London|date=3 November 1999|accessdate=6 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nA combination of injuries<ref name=Retire>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/c/chelsea/3011409.stm|title=Ferrer set to retire|publisher=BBC Sport|date=8 May 2003|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref> and manager [[Gianluca Vialli]]'s squad rotation policy reduced Ferrer's opportunities in [[2000\u201301 FA Premier League|2000\u201301]], and he made only 14 league appearances. Chelsea [[2002 FA Cup Final|reached another FA Cup final]] in [[2001\u201302 FA Cup|2002]] \u2013 which he again missed, though this time through not being selected, despite playing in the semi-final against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/apr/15/match.sport12|title=Terry bundles the Blues to Cardiff|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Jon|last=Brodkin|date=15 April 2002|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Out of favour and facing strong competition from younger teammates he played just seven times in his final two years, and left in May 2003 upon the expiry of his contract, totalling 113 overall matches for the [[London]]ers and retiring shortly after at 33.<ref name=Retire/>\n\n===International===\nFerrer was a [[Spain national football team|Spain international]] on 36 occasions. His debut came on 4 September 1991 in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win with [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in [[Oviedo]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1991/09/05/pagina-7/1245811/pdf.html|title=Tiempo de llorar, tiempo de so\u00f1ar|trans-title=A time to cry, a time to dream|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Fabi\u00e1n|last=Ortiz|language=Spanish|date=5 September 1991|accessdate=20 March 2014}}</ref> as ''La Roja'' eventually did not qualify for [[UEFA Euro 1992]].\n\nSubsequently, Ferrer was a regular figure in the national side, appearing as starter at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] and playing once in [[1998 FIFA World Cup|the 1998 edition]], the 2\u20133 group stage loss against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]], missing [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]] and [[UEFA Euro 2000|2000]] through injury (with Barcelona teammate Sergi on the other flank in all these tournaments).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/spain/748444.stm|title=Camacho blow for Ferrer|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 May 2000|accessdate=17 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Ferrer was first-choice for the [[Spain national under-23 football team|Olympic team]] that [[Football at the 1992 Summer Olympics|won the gold medal]] at the [[1992 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]], held in his hometown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dameunsilbidito.enlaweb.eu/2010/04/el-triunfo-en-el-futbol-broche-de-oro-para-espana-en-barcelona-92/|title=El triunfo en el f\u00fatbol, broche de oro para Espa\u00f1a en Barcelona 92|trans-title=Football win, icing on the cake for Spain in Barcelona 92|publisher=Dame Un Silbidito|language=Spanish|date=April 2010|accessdate=30 May 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320202410/http://dameunsilbidito.enlaweb.eu/2010/04/el-triunfo-en-el-futbol-broche-de-oro-para-espana-en-barcelona-92/|archive-date=20 March 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.antena3.com/el-blog-de-miss-forty/roja-1992-nuestra-medalla-oro-olimpica_2012070300083.html|title=La Roja de 1992, nuestra medalla de oro Ol\u00edmpica|trans-title=1992's ''La Roja'', our Olympic gold medal|publisher=[[Antena 3 (Spain)|Antena 3]]|language=Spanish|date=3 July 2012|accessdate=13 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nAfter retiring, Ferrer worked as a [[color commentator]] for a number of Spanish broadcasters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infoperiodistas.info/noticia/3038/La-Sexta-ficha-a-Salinas-Kiko-Chapi-Ferrer-y-Maceda|title=La Sexta ficha a Salinas, Kiko, Chapi Ferrer y Maceda|trans-title=La Sexta signs Salinas, Kiko, Chapi Ferrer and Maceda|publisher=Info Periodistas|language=Spanish|date=29 August 2006|accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> In late October 2010, he was announced as new head coach of [[SBV Vitesse]] in the [[Eredivisie]], his staff also including compatriot Albert Capellas (formerly youth coach at Barcelona) and former Dutch [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Stanley Menzo]], who left his post at [[SC Cambuur]] in order to join the Spaniards.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/telesport/voetbal/vitesse/8042665/__Oud-Baraspeler_Ferrer_volgt_Bos_op__.html?p=2,2Oud-Barcelonaspeler|title=Oud-Barcelonaspeler Ferrer opvolger trainer Bos|trans-title=Former Barcelona player Ferrer is Bos' successor|newspaper=[[De Telegraaf]]|language=Dutch|date=27 October 2010|accessdate=30 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nFerrer led the side to [[2010\u201311 Eredivisie|the 15th position]], in a narrow escape from relegation. He was subsequently relieved of his duties, being replaced by [[John van den Brom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vitesse.nl/nieuws/bericht/vitesse-en-ferrer-gaan-uit-elkaar/1579|title=Vitesse en Ferrer gaan uit elkaar|trans-title=Vitesse and Ferrer part company|publisher=SBV Vitesse|language=Dutch|date=22 June 2011|accessdate=30 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626190551/http://www.vitesse.nl/nieuws/bericht/vitesse-en-ferrer-gaan-uit-elkaar/1579|archivedate=26 June 2011|df=dmy}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 February 2014, Ferrer was appointed at [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] club [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cordobacf.com/-/albert-ferrer-nuevo-entrenador-del-cordoba-c-f- |title=Albert Ferrer nuevo entrenador del C\u00f3rdoba C.F.|trans-title=Albert Ferrer new C\u00f3rdoba C.F. manager|publisher=C\u00f3rdoba CF|language=Spanish|date=17 February 2014|accessdate=17 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302114455/http://www.cordobacf.com/-/albert-ferrer-nuevo-entrenador-del-cordoba-c-f-|archivedate=2 March 2014}}</ref> After [[2013\u201314 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|finishing the season in the seventh place]], they defeated [[UD Las Palmas]] in [[2014 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n play-offs|the play-off final]] to return to the top flight for the first time in 42 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/138/spain/2014/06/23/4905144/las-palmas-cordoba-la-liga-play-off-ends-with-pitch-invasion|title=Las Palmas-Cordoba La Liga play-off ends with pitch invasion|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=23 June 2014|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://sevilla.abc.es/andalucia/cordoba/20140623/sevp-heroes-ascenso-20140623.html|title=Los h\u00e9roes del ascenso|trans-title=The promotion heroes|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=Spanish|date=23 June 2014|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nFerrer was fired on 20 October 2014, as C\u00f3rdoba [[2014\u201315 La Liga|ranked dead last with only four points in eight matches]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/130933/cordoba-cf-sack-albert-ferrer-as-manager/|title=C\u00f3rdoba CF sack Albert Ferrer as manager|publisher=Inside Spanish Football|first=Heath|last=Chesters|date=20 October 2014|accessdate=20 October 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021063351/http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/130933/cordoba-cf-sack-albert-ferrer-as-manager/|archive-date=21 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 20 June of the following year he was named [[RCD Mallorca]] manager, signing a one-year deal;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=34248&idmenu=3|title=Chapi Ferrer presentado como entrenador del Mallorca|trans-title=Chapi Ferrer presented as manager of Mallorca|publisher=RCD Mallorca|language=Spanish|date=20 June 2015|accessdate=21 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622025657/http://rcdmallorca.es/principal_new.php?nombreModulo=noticiasDetalle&idnoticia=34248&idmenu=3|archivedate=22 June 2015}}</ref> after three wins from 15 second level games, he was dismissed on 30 November.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.diariodemallorca.es/rcd-mallorca/2015/11/30/mallorca-destituye-albert-ferrer-entrenado/1075032.html|title=El Real Mallorca destituye a Albert \u00b4Chapi\u00b4 Ferrer como entrenador|trans-title=Real Mallorca dismiss Albert 'Chapi' Ferrer as manager|newspaper=Diario de Mallorca|language=Spanish|date=30 November 2015|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2017, Ferrer returned to Barcelona as coach of its legends team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/club/news/2017-2018/albert-ferrer-to-coach-barca-legends|title=Albert Ferrer to coach Bar\u00e7a Legends|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=29 August 2017|accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|28 November 2015}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\t\t\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Team\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Nat\n!rowspan=\"2\"|From\n!rowspan=\"2\"|To\n!colspan=\"8\"|Record\t\n|-\t\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=left|[[SBV Vitesse|Vitesse]] \n|{{flagicon|Netherlands}}\n|align=left|27 October 2010\n|align=left|30 June 2011\n{{WDL|25|8|6|11|for=35|against=42|diff=yes}}\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=left|[[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l50.html?temp=2013-14 |title=Ferrer: Albert Ferrer Llopis|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=23 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l50.html?temp=2014-15|ti